ACHP Seeks Applicants for Executive Director Post
ACHP to Host Virtual Business Meeting June 29
Read More About The Federal Preservation Process
Before a review begins, the federal agency must decide if Section 106 applies.
The federal agency identifies who should be involved in consultation and plans to involve the public.
The federal agency identifies historic properties in the area where the project could have effects.
The federal agency consults to assess the effects of the project on historic properties.
The federal agency explores alternatives to avoid, minimize, or mitigate adverse effects.
Before a review begins, the federal agency must decide if Section 106 applies.
The federal agency identifies who should be involved in consultation and plans to involve the public.
The federal agency identifies historic properties in the area where the project could have effects.
The federal agency consults to assess the effects of the project on historic properties.
The federal agency explores alternatives to avoid, minimize, or mitigate adverse effects.

By creating partnerships with local schools and offering unique opportunities to students, the ACHP hopes to educate young people on preservation and encourage them to enjoy history in their own backyards.

Because the demographics of America are always changing, the ACHP strives to build a more inclusive preservation program. By widening the representation of the diverse cultures and encouraging involvement in all available opportunities.

Historic properties throughout the country are threatened by increasing climate impacts. The ACHP is working to help ensure that the federal government addresses historic properties in its climate resilience and sustainability policies and programs.
Read More About Climate Change & Sustainability
The ACHP supports federal policies and programs that promote use of historic properties to revitalize local communities.
Read More About Community Revitalization & Economic Benefits

As the number of skilled workers in the construction trades has plummeted in recent years, the shortage of skilled preservation craft workers has continued to grow. Restoration work on historic buildings simply cannot be done without skilled workers, making the training of new craftspeople a critical priority.
Read More About Traditional Trades Training

standards: Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0, Level A: 2.4.4 Link Purpose (In Context)
Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0, Level AAA: 2.4.9 Link Purpose (Link Only)
resultSet.resultTitle: Don't reuse the same link text for links that have different destinations
resultSet.errorDescription: This link has the same text as another link that goes to a different place. Using the same text for multiple links which point to different pages is ambiguous and may be confusing for assistive technology users, or for users who have a cognitive disability. Link text should tell the user where they will go if they follow the link. If two links on a page go to two different destinations, use different link text that accurately and concisely describes their destination.

resultSet.errorTitle: This content's line height is insufficent to properly display the computed element font size.
standards: Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.0, Level AAA: 1.4.8 Visual Presentation
resultSet.resultTitle: Set a `line-height` (leading) that is at least one and a half times the current font size.
resultSet.errorDescription: This content's line height is insufficent to properly display the computed element font size. Line height that is less than 150% of the computed element font size limits content readability for people with dyslexia, low vision, cognitive impairments or learning disabilities. Set the `line-height` for this content to a value of 1.5 or higher. Using a proportional, unitless value like 1.5 or 150% will ensure that the line-height scales if the user zooms the browser window.
